          "title": "The Lord's oath — covenant permanence and conditional obedience",
          "body": "The psalm's structural pivot is v. 11: 'The Lord has sworn to David a truth from which He will not turn back.' Human vow (v. 2) has been answered by divine oath (v. 11), and the divine oath is categorically superior in authority and reliability. The content of the oath (vv. 11-12) is drawn from 2 Samuel 7:12-16 and Psalm 89:3-4 — a descendant will occupy David's throne. But v. 12 introduces a conditional element: 'If your sons will keep My covenant and My testimony which I will teach them, their sons also shall sit upon your throne forever.' Reformed interpreters (Calvin, Moo) and classical Arminian interpreters read the tension differently here. The Reformed reading sees the conditional clause governing the specific form of blessing in each generation's experience (individual kings may forfeit their reign) while the unconditional promise of a perpetual dynasty guarantees that the line will never entirely fail. The Arminian reading takes the condition more uniformly as governing the covenant's continuation itself, accounting for historical discontinuities. Both must reckon with the New Testament's resolution: the conditionality is absorbed by the One Son who perfectly kept the covenant, securing the throne unconditionally for Himself (Acts 2:30-31; Luke 1:32-33)."
